I made this without the vermouth and butter, for no particular reason other than laziness. It was still delicious. The fresh herbs really make it. I used what I had on hand - Thai basil, parsley, rosemary, oregano, chives.

Rating: 3
I suppose I shouldn't review this because I changed the method somewhat, but for the sake of those who are looking for a good marinade, I will. I combined all of the ingredients (except the white wine/butter for the sauce) and left it overnight in the refrigerator. Then I broiled the chicken. The chicken was so delicious, moist and full of flavor. This is one of my go-to marinades for a weeknight meal.

Rating: 3
I really enjoyed the light, fresh taste of the chicken. We wound up using parsley, thyme, and rosemary on the chicken, since we had some from our garden. It went really well with the grilled veggies we made--asparagus, zucchini, squash, and green beans. It really is quite good for a summer bbq, if you want to keep the meal light for the summer.

Rating: 4
Loved this recipe! And it is really easy (but again yes the smoke). Used dried herbs (40% parsely, 40% oregano, 10% thyme, 10% dill) and added ~1/2 tsp crushed pepper for a bit of bite. Also subbed with sherry vs sherry vinegar. Had to broil for a bit longer than what was recommended. A major hit with the sigo, and will likely enter our rotation!

Rating: 4
Maybe this is a whole different recipe created from the one listed here... I don't know, but it was amazing! I created a marinade from the olive oil, Dijon mustard, salt, herbs (parsley, rosemary, tarragon, chives, marjoram, thyme... I have a plentiful herb garden), cream sherry instead of sherry wine vinegar, and a splash of balsamic. Marinated the chicken for about an hour in that mixture. Shook off the marinade and grilled the chicken for 12 minutes (6 min each side). It was tender and juicy. Tossed mushrooms into a saute pan with some butter and parsley, then added the remaining marinade, vermouth and butter called for in the recipe. I let it reduce, adding a pinch of arrowroot to thicken. Put a nice portion of greens on a plate, sliced the chicken and put it on top of the greens, then added the sauce. WOW. This was amazing. If you like the flavor of fresh herbs as much as I do, you'll love it.

